Based on the retrieved evidence, there is no mention of celecoxib being studied or showing effectiveness in treating amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS). While celecoxib is recognized as a selective COX-2 inhibitor used primarily for osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis, and dysmenorrhea, none of the references indicate any investigation into its efficacy for ALS symptom management or disease modification. The primary treatments discussed for ALS remain riluzole, edaravone, and sodium phenylbutyrate—all of which have established roles in slowing progression—but celecoxib is absent from any trial or recommendation related to ALS. Therefore, despite its general use in inflammation-related conditions, there is insufficient evidence to suggest it plays a role in ALS treatment.
